âœ… 1ï¸âƒ£ What is Scope?
Scope means:
ğŸ‘‰ Where a variable can be accessed in a program.
There are mainly:
Local Scope
Global Scope
(Advanced: Enclosing & Built-in â€” LEGB rule)

âœ… 2ï¸âƒ£ Local Scope
A variable created inside a function is called a local variable.
It can only be used inside that function.
ğŸ”¹ Example of Local Scope
def greet():
    message = "Hello DevOps"
    print(message)

greet()
ğŸ”¥ Output:
Hello DevOps
But:
print(message)  # âŒ Error  
ğŸ‘‰ Error because message is local to greet().

âœ… 3ï¸âƒ£ Global Scope
A variable created outside all functions is called a global variable.
It can be accessed anywhere in the program.
ğŸ”¹ Example of Global Scope
server_name = "web1"

def show_server():
    print(server_name)

show_server()
ğŸ”¥ Output:
web1
Here:
server_name is global
Function can access it

âš ï¸ Important: Modifying Global Variable
If you try to change a global variable inside a function:
count = 10
def update():
    count = count + 1   # âŒ Error
It will give error.
To modify global variable, use global keyword.

ğŸ”¹ Using global Keyword
count = 10

def update():
    global count
    count = count + 1

update()
print(count)
ğŸ”¥ Output:
11

âœ… 4ï¸âƒ£ Local vs Global Example (Important)
value = 100  # Global

def test():
    value = 50   # Local
    print("Inside function:", value)

test()
print("Outside function:", value)
ğŸ”¥ Output:
Inside function: 50
Outside function: 100

âœ… 5ï¸âƒ£ DevOps Example â€“ CPU Monitor
threshold = 80   # Global variable

def check_cpu(cpu_usage):
    if cpu_usage > threshold:
        return "High CPU"
    return "Normal"

print(check_cpu(75))

Here:
threshold is global
Used inside function

âœ… 7ï¸âƒ£ Better Professional Way
Instead of global:
def start_server(status):
    return "running"

server_status = "stopped"
server_status = start_server(server_status)
print(server_status)

âœ… 8ï¸âƒ£ LEGB Rule (Interview Important)
Python checks variables in this order:
L â†’ Local
E â†’ Enclosing (nested functions)
G â†’ Global
B â†’ Built-in
ğŸ”¹ Example of LEGB
x = "global"

def outer():
    x = "enclosing"

    def inner():
        x = "local"
        print(x)

    inner()

outer()
Output:
local
